<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10088d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10088d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10088d"> 88(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> higher less danger</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Flying in Ireland / Illusions That Hinder Progress <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font></b> There is the idea that flying is an experience of dashing, thrilling speed. The fact is that in flight at an ordinary flying height of, say, 5,000 feet, the sense of great speed is practically nil.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Movement through the air at, say, 60 m.p.h. seems very much slower than the same speed over ground.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It is an immense surprise on a first flight to find that there is practically no sense of danger. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The writer believes it to be due to the <mark>failure of the imagination to suggest danger once a certain height</mark> has been reached. <small> <a name="IS26apr24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IS26apr24"><cite title="source">Irish Statesman</cite></a> (26 April 1924) 217/1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
